WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.040
My name is David Aja. I'm a member of the solutions engineering team at RStudio, or

00:00:11.040 --> 00:00:19.480
if you prefer, I posit solutions. I help data scientists get their ideas into production,

00:00:19.480 --> 00:00:23.719
and in the course of doing that work, I see a lot of broken things. And so that's why

00:00:23.719 --> 00:00:32.000
today I'll be talking about why I think you should use renv. Probably.

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:35.759
So there are two parts to this talk. The first part is going to be about why I think you

00:00:35.759 --> 00:00:39.880
should do this, and then in the second part we'll talk about how. But let's start with

00:00:39.880 --> 00:00:46.480
why. And I think the reason that I'm kind of up here giving this talk is because I think

00:00:46.480 --> 00:00:51.200
we have a standards problem. And the way I would express that standards problem is that

00:00:51.200 --> 00:00:55.520
I don't know if we have a good answer to the following question, which is what makes

00:00:55.520 --> 00:01:03.439
a project an R project? We're probably going to need to define some terms in order to sort

00:01:03.439 --> 00:01:08.440
of make our way through that. So let's start with project. What is a project? This is the

00:01:08.440 --> 00:01:13.400
definition you get if you Google it, right? We've got an individual or collaborative enterprise

00:01:13.400 --> 00:01:18.040
aimed at a particular aim. I think that's a pretty helpful definition. But sometimes

00:01:18.040 --> 00:01:24.599
I like to try to define things functionally, right? A thing is what it does. And so what

00:01:24.599 --> 00:01:32.720
do projects do? Projects ship. This is a slightly unusual way of talking. It's kind of a legacy

00:01:32.720 --> 00:01:39.440
of our history of writing software to physical media and then mailing it to your house. But

00:01:39.440 --> 00:01:43.400
this is kind of the paradigm that we have in mind when we talk about shipping projects,

00:01:43.400 --> 00:01:47.519
right? We've worked on something. I have it. I need to get it to you, and I want you to

00:01:47.519 --> 00:01:54.919
have a particular experience. Some of you may be thinking about like a particular file

00:01:54.919 --> 00:02:01.040
extension that maybe you're like, it says that kind of thing there. And so I'll just

00:02:01.040 --> 00:02:08.720
say I think the .rproj or the RStudio project file is not going to be sufficient for our

00:02:08.720 --> 00:02:13.679
purposes here. And part of the reason that's true is because what's in the RStudio project

00:02:13.679 --> 00:02:19.679
file is editor configuration. And editor configuration is important to you. But when

00:02:19.679 --> 00:02:26.119
you send data analysis results to someone, they typically don't ask you how many spaces

00:02:26.119 --> 00:02:32.360
you put in a tab, right? And so the idea is you don't ship your editor. A thing I think

00:02:32.360 --> 00:02:37.880
it's important to say, right? I'm making a lot of declarative statements here. Part of

00:02:37.880 --> 00:02:44.399
this is from a history of screwing things up pretty catastrophically. So I have actually

00:02:44.399 --> 00:02:50.279
shipped my editor. And then I ended up debugging my code in our general counsel's office. And

00:02:50.279 --> 00:02:54.440
that's not where I want any of you to be, right? So I think we have to look for some

00:02:54.440 --> 00:03:00.839
better ways of doing work, right? So, you know, the RStudio project file is going to

00:03:00.839 --> 00:03:05.479
be necessary if you use RStudio. And I think an important thing to acknowledge, even though

00:03:05.479 --> 00:03:10.199
this is RStudioConf, is that not everyone does use RStudio, right? The RStudio project

00:03:10.199 --> 00:03:15.160
file is necessary. But for the purpose of helping us understand what a project is, it's

00:03:15.160 --> 00:03:21.119
not going to be sufficient, right? So we have to look elsewhere for a definition of what

00:03:21.119 --> 00:03:26.119
a project is. And one of the things that I found really inspiring when I was trying to

00:03:26.119 --> 00:03:33.199
figure out how to more reliably deliver software was a website called 12factor.net. This website

00:03:33.199 --> 00:03:38.279
was published by people who work on the deployment platform Heroku, which helped people deploy

00:03:38.279 --> 00:03:44.279
software as a service applications to the public. But a lot of the lessons that they

00:03:44.279 --> 00:03:48.720
published there, I think, are useful even in the data professional context. And one

00:03:48.720 --> 00:03:53.600
of the things they really stress is the importance of environment isolation, right? So the 12

00:03:53.600 --> 00:03:58.360
factor apps never rely on the implicit existence of system-wide packages. And there are a couple

00:03:58.360 --> 00:04:02.360
of things that they say are important to making this happen, right? So you have to declare

00:04:02.360 --> 00:04:07.080
all your dependencies, and then you have to isolate them from other things on the system.

00:04:07.080 --> 00:04:11.039
And you have to make sure that no implicit dependencies leak in. And I want to dwell

00:04:11.039 --> 00:04:16.000
on the leak in thing for a moment, because I'm going to give a sort of stylized example

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:20.959
from my past to show you how this kind of thing can happen, right? So let's say, you

00:04:20.959 --> 00:04:26.519
know, or let's say I was working on a project. I did a lot of work on the 2020 census for

00:04:26.519 --> 00:04:32.040
an advertising agency I worked on at the time. And I delivered some dashboard, and people

00:04:32.040 --> 00:04:39.000
looked at the results, and it was good. And then someone asked me to do some data analysis

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:44.239
on the census tract level. It needed to do between a one and seven day look back. There

00:04:44.239 --> 00:04:50.679
were like 80,000 census tracts. We were doing data analysis for, at that point, several

00:04:50.679 --> 00:04:55.559
months worth of data. And so I was like, OK, I need to do something. This might be a good

00:04:55.559 --> 00:05:04.040
case for the latest DTPlier. And so I installed DTPlier. I was able to work on the analysis,

00:05:04.040 --> 00:05:12.859
and everything was fine. Except I accidentally, by installing DTPlier, upgraded the version

00:05:12.859 --> 00:05:16.880
of DPlier that was being used in my dashboard, because the thing I haven't highlighted so

00:05:16.880 --> 00:05:29.040
far is that we have a dependency on a shared user library. The answer is not in production.

00:05:29.040 --> 00:05:34.119
And so I think I'm going to borrow Julia's excellent metaphor from yesterday. We want

00:05:34.119 --> 00:05:39.760
to find a way of working that stops it from being possible for us to lock our keys in

00:05:39.760 --> 00:05:45.959
the car. So let's talk about how we do that, right? The first step is going to be to isolate

00:05:46.040 --> 00:05:51.399
your dependencies. And so in order to do that, you're going to need to install the renv package.

00:05:51.399 --> 00:05:54.519
And then you're going to initialize it. You have a couple of options for doing that. You

00:05:54.519 --> 00:05:58.640
can call the init function. There's also a little box you can check as you're creating

00:05:58.640 --> 00:06:03.880
a new project in the RStudio IDE. And that will create, and this will sort of overwrite

00:06:03.880 --> 00:06:09.760
your libpaths, right? So by default, you have kind of a user library and a system library.

00:06:09.760 --> 00:06:14.720
And renv will take that over and say, OK, now you have a project-specific library. And

00:06:14.720 --> 00:06:19.600
then your system library. And so what that looks like, if we go back in time, I properly

00:06:19.600 --> 00:06:25.239
isolate my libraries. I have this user library in my dashboard. And then the project library

00:06:25.239 --> 00:06:31.040
gets the upgraded versions. And that means that if I start working on new projects, say

00:06:31.040 --> 00:06:37.000
I start doing experimental things with new packages and tidy models, I'm not really concerned

00:06:37.000 --> 00:06:41.600
about breaking other things in my workflow. And the other thing that's nice to note here

00:06:41.600 --> 00:06:46.119
is that you can adopt this incrementally. So you don't have to move all of your projects

00:06:46.119 --> 00:06:51.320
at once. You can see that my dashboard is still pointing in my user library. I can go

00:06:51.320 --> 00:06:54.799
and upgrade that surgically later on if I want to.

00:06:54.799 --> 00:06:59.320
And you might be asking yourself, OK, well, you're making me maintain this isolated library.

00:06:59.320 --> 00:07:04.200
Does that mean I need to reinstall every package from scratch each time? The answer is no.

00:07:04.200 --> 00:07:09.119
Renv maintains a package cache. So once you install a package, it's available to you to

00:07:09.119 --> 00:07:13.399
reuse in other projects if they have the same dependency. So that first installation

00:07:13.399 --> 00:07:20.720
might take a little bit of time. But subsequent installations will go much faster.

00:07:20.720 --> 00:07:24.959
Once we've isolated the dependencies on our system, the next thing we need to do is to

00:07:24.959 --> 00:07:30.000
discover what they are and write that down somewhere. And so calling the renv snapshot

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:34.279
function is going to give us some information about the versions of packages we use and

00:07:34.279 --> 00:07:42.640
which ones we have, where we got those packages from. Because as we've heard, shared drives,

00:07:42.640 --> 00:07:47.079
RStudio Package Manager, the R universe, all of these are different places where you can

00:07:47.079 --> 00:07:51.959
get R packages. And so you want to be able to keep track of where you got them, as well

00:07:51.959 --> 00:07:54.720
as the version of R you were using for your project.

00:07:54.720 --> 00:07:59.640
And so you can see here, this is a package I've installed from the R universe. And so

00:07:59.640 --> 00:08:03.559
we're keeping track of the information about the git commit. And we're writing all of this

00:08:03.559 --> 00:08:08.959
down in the renv lock file. And I think the renv lock file is the project artifact that

00:08:08.959 --> 00:08:13.239
we're looking for. Part of the thing that it's going to enable

00:08:13.239 --> 00:08:18.519
us to do is to collaborate more effectively. And so renv is itself very helpful in giving

00:08:18.519 --> 00:08:22.760
you status messages about what you need to do next. And this is going to be really helpful

00:08:22.760 --> 00:08:26.799
for contexts where either you're picking up an old project or you're sharing a project

00:08:26.799 --> 00:08:31.140
with a teammate who doesn't have the same package set on their computer.

00:08:31.140 --> 00:08:36.020
So you can see in this case, I've installed some packages, or I'm sorry, I've pulled down

00:08:36.020 --> 00:08:40.340
a lock file. And packages are in the lock file, but they're not yet on my system. And

00:08:40.340 --> 00:08:44.859
renv is going to tell me what to do. And this is a similar kind of situation where I started

00:08:44.859 --> 00:08:49.219
using a package, but I haven't installed it yet. Calling renv status is, again, going

00:08:49.219 --> 00:08:54.859
to tell me what to do to get right. And if I remove a package from my project,

00:08:54.859 --> 00:08:59.179
then I want to remove those dependencies as well, because I don't want to ship unnecessary

00:08:59.260 --> 00:09:04.460
things to my deployment target, whatever that is. And so this is going to be the workflow.

00:09:04.460 --> 00:09:10.140
We're going to initialize a project in renv, we'll install the packages we need, we snapshot,

00:09:10.140 --> 00:09:16.299
we ship, and then later we can restore that environment. Once we have the project in renv,

00:09:16.299 --> 00:09:22.539
install, snapshot, ship, and restore. I did say probably at the beginning. There

00:09:22.539 --> 00:09:28.059
are a couple of things where this may not apply to you. One, I'll call it a bad argument,

00:09:28.059 --> 00:09:35.659
and one better one. I don't intend to reuse this code. This is too much overhead. I think

00:09:35.659 --> 00:09:39.380
one of the things about being a data professional is that you are, in fact, going to have to

00:09:39.380 --> 00:09:43.659
reuse the code. Someone is going to ask you, hey, I got numbers from finance that don't

00:09:43.659 --> 00:09:47.099
match yours. What's going on? Can you rediscover that? And you're just like, you're going to

00:09:47.099 --> 00:09:52.539
be in that cycle of iteration. And so this is a tweet I pulled from somebody

00:09:52.539 --> 00:09:56.739
who was talking about this as I was avoiding working on this talk. And I think it really

00:09:56.739 --> 00:10:00.780
perfectly encapsulates that if you just treat things like they're throwaway, they're going

00:10:00.780 --> 00:10:05.940
to come back, and you should just work like your work is valuable.

00:10:05.940 --> 00:10:11.539
If you are purely a package developer, then you are in a somewhat different circumstance,

00:10:11.539 --> 00:10:17.619
because the execution target is not necessarily like getting someone to call your plumber API.

00:10:17.619 --> 00:10:24.659
It's CRAN reverse dependency checks. Renv does have some tools that you can use to isolate

00:10:24.659 --> 00:10:29.380
environments if you need to do specialized testing. And the article in that on the Rnv

00:10:29.380 --> 00:10:33.780
documentation is pretty excellent, as is the rest of Rnv's documentation.

00:10:33.780 --> 00:10:38.900
So in summary, I think we have an opportunity here to coalesce on a project standard. I

00:10:38.900 --> 00:10:44.260
encourage you all to use Rnv. And I want to say a special thank you to Kevin, without

00:10:44.260 --> 00:10:47.179
whose work none of this would be possible. Thank you.

